{
  "texts": [
    "Working with periodic boundary conditions and focusing on the Liouvillian rapidity gap κ we find a clear dichotomy: uniform dissipation produces large, weakly λ-dependent gaps while sparse local dissipation yields gaps that collapse rapidly as λ induces localization.",
    "Increasing helical hopping t N counteracts localization effects and increases κ. Finitesize scaling, level-statistics crossovers, and slow-mode profiles form a consistent diagnostic suite linking Liouvillian spectral structure to transport and localization.These findings are directly relevant for reservoir engineering protocols in photonic, superconducting, and coldatom platforms where both quasiperiodic potentials and site-resolved dissipation are available [9,11,14,15].",
    "Future work could (i) develop analytical weak-dissipation golden-rule estimates for κ, (ii) explore interacting perturbations beyond quadratic models, and (iii) propose explicit experimental protocols to measure κ (via relaxation traces or Liouvillian spectroscopy) and use it as a sensing resource [10,12].0.0 0.5 1.0 1.5 2.0 λ 0.00 0.05 0.10 0.15 Rapidity gap (Re) tN = 0.0 tN = 0.25 tN = 0.5 tN = 0.75 tN = 1.0 tN = 1.5 0.0 0.5 1.0 1.5 2.0 λ 0.0000 0.0005 0.0010 0.0015 Rapidity gap (Re) tN = 0.0 tN = 0.25 tN = 0.5 tN = 0.75 tN = 1.0 tN = 1.5 0.0 0.5 1.0 1.5 2.0 λ 0.000 0.001 0.002 0.003 Rapidity gap (Re) tN = 0.0 tN = 0.25 tN = 0.5 tN = 0.75 tN = 1.0 tN = 1.5FIG.",
    "1: Linecuts of the Liouvillian rapidity κ versus quasiperiodic potential strength λ for several values of the long-range hopping amplitude t N. Each curve corresponds to one t N (legend in each panel).",
    "All data were obtained under periodic boundary conditions."
  ]
}